FortyTwo BBS Development Roadmap
================================

Current status
--------------

FortyTwo BBS is pre-alpha software intended for development, code review and
isolated testing.

The currently tested development environment is:

- Ubuntu 25.10
- x86_64
- glibc-based Linux
- rootless Podman test operation on the development host

There is no supported production installation, public deployment or upgrade
procedure yet.

This roadmap describes current development priorities. It is not a promise
that every item will be completed for the first public test release.


Established foundations
-----------------------

The following foundations have already been implemented or verified:

- rootless Podman test image builds and starts successfully
- fixed service accounts are used for the current container test runtime
- BBS users are planned as internal application identities rather than
  personal Unix or container accounts
- `mbuseradd` and `mbpasswd` are excluded from the normal build and install
  path
- `mbtask` is installed without setuid or setgid bits
- `mbtask` checks and performs privilege dropping
- raw ICMP monitoring can be disabled with `MBSE_DISABLE_RAW_PING=1`
- deleted and locked BBS accounts are rejected before session startup
- transitional environment-name handling in `mbsebbs` is bounded
- localhost-only Telnet and restricted SSH access have been tested
- SSH command execution, forwarding and additional interactive features are
  restricted
- AddressSanitizer and UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer builds are used during
  review
- English and German security architecture documents have been created
- English and German project and developer documentation have been combined
  into `README.md` and `LIESMICH.md`


Immediate security priorities
-----------------------------

- remove plaintext password display from administration screens and generated
  output
- remove passwords and other secrets from logs
- review password exposure in door dropfiles and offline-mail formats
- disable or replace independent plaintext authentication paths
- review NNTP authentication, account-state checks and rate limiting
- continue reviewing unsafe string, buffer and memory handling
- review network-facing parsers and archive handling
- define security logging, audit events and rate-limiting requirements
- review filesystem ownership, permissions and persistent storage
- ensure no setuid-root or setgid BBS helper programs remain in the supported
  runtime


Identity and authentication
---------------------------

- replace mutable Unix-name-based identity handling
- introduce stable, opaque and server-generated user IDs
- separate login identifiers, display names and internal user IDs
- store users, credentials, roles, sessions and audit events in a transactional
  database
- define and implement database migrations and foreign-key constraints
- use Argon2id for password hashing
- support optional TOTP multi-factor authentication
- introduce rotating, revocable and server-side session credentials
- centralize authentication, account-state, role and capability checks
- replace display-name-based sysop detection with roles and capabilities
- stop trusting environment variables, command-line arguments or mutable
  names as authenticated session identity
- design an authenticated local session handoff for terminal transports
- migrate user storage from mutable names to stable internal IDs
- define a safe migration path from historical `users.data` records


Installation and deployment
---------------------------

- replace the inherited `SETUP.sh` installation procedure
- create a reproducible Ubuntu 25.10 development setup
- complete and document the rootless Podman test deployment
- prepare Debian as the first planned container deployment target
- define persistent storage for configuration, users, messages and files
- provide service supervision and clean container shutdown
- document backup and restore procedures
- define image updates, database migrations and rollback behaviour
- create a supported upgrade and migration process
- test additional Linux distributions and BSD after the first release


Telnet, SSH and user access
---------------------------

- retain Telnet as a supported terminal transport
- retain restricted SSH access for registered BBS users
- keep SSH command execution, forwarding, tunnelling, SCP and SFTP disabled
- integrate the final access configuration into deployment tooling
- remove the dependency on personal operating-system accounts
- implement registration entirely inside the BBS identity system
- keep public self-registration disabled until the replacement is complete
- review logout and session-accounting behaviour
- test uploads and downloads through supported terminal clients
- test concurrent sessions, interrupted sessions and forced termination


File areas and importing
------------------------

- continue testing recursive file-tree importing
- preserve directory structure and file-area relationships
- verify `FILES.BBS` parsing with real-world archives
- test multiline descriptions and maximum field lengths
- improve error reporting and recovery during imports
- test duplicate files, malformed metadata and unusual filenames
- review character-set conversion for CP437 and UTF-8 descriptions
- test file checking, packing and adoption workflows
- document generated HTML indexes, downloads and image previews


Fidonet and messaging
---------------------

- verify mailer, tosser and TIC processing on current systems
- test message bases, echomail, netmail and file distribution
- review packet passwords, logging and secret handling
- review network-facing parsers and protocol handling
- test BinkP and legacy Fidonet transport functions
- document supported Fidonet configuration and operating procedures


Web publishing
--------------

- document static HTML generation for file areas
- provide a separate web-server deployment
- publish generated indexes and downloadable files read-only where possible
- define safe shared storage between FortyTwo BBS and the web server
- test download accounting from external web-server logs
- ensure web publishing cannot expose credentials or private BBS data


Build system and naming
-----------------------

- modernize the inherited Autoconf and Make build system
- replace remaining public MBSE branding with FortyTwo BBS
- retain historical attribution and license information
- review inherited technical names such as `MBSE_ROOT` and `mbsebbs`
- define package name, versioning and release archive format
- remove obsolete platform claims and distribution instructions
- keep generated files synchronized with their source templates
- add reproducible clean-build and sanitizer-build checks


Developer interfaces
--------------------

- define a versioned, self-hosted API for native clients and external tools
- identify stable public interfaces and internal implementation details
- prohibit direct modification of historical binary data files by new tools
- document authentication, sessions, roles and capabilities
- define stable identifiers for users, messages, files and areas
- define interfaces for Doors, clients and administration tools
- document Telnet, SSH, NNTP, Fidonet and web integration
- define coding and security requirements for extensions
- provide versioning, deprecation and compatibility rules
- create example programs and reproducible test environments


Documentation and release preparation
-------------------------------------

- audit all user-visible text, templates and generated documentation
- replace obsolete websites, support addresses and project references
- review and update `FILE_ID.DIZ.in` before the first release
- review language files, menus, templates and ANSI screens
- verify every installation and operating instruction
- document known limitations and unsupported features
- create release notes and a tested first-release checklist
- perform clean installation tests before publishing downloadable releases
- keep `README.md` and `LIESMICH.md` synchronized
- keep `SECURITY_ARCHITECTURE.md` and `SICHERHEITS_ARCHITEKTUR.md`
  synchronized


Project information
-------------------

Project & Source:  https://github.com/Juergen-Coding/FortyTwoBBS
Support: https://github.com/Juergen-Coding/FortyTwoBBS/issues
